Local Engagement as a Countermeasure Against Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated the Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing election defeats.
Other have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments resemble each other everywhere in the West.
The leaderships of the once dominant parties oscillate between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their opponents' supporters as "pitiable," as Hillary Clinton did shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too frightened by the populist tide to launch a counteroffensive.
Yet neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the stalled political situation.
The Progressives must regroup, and that begins with diagnosing the shortcomings of the traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the increasing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that actually matter to voters.
They were the vanguard decades ago.
Today they stand alone in the forest, wondering where everyone has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The chasm between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened into an abyss.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the growing disparity in income and other indicators between some wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
Yet before the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national prime minister had implemented tax cuts based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
The traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and polling institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the questioners then became the basis of Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct toward women, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of jokes by his opponents; however, the laughter quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not sufficient.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and cheer on the candidates.
That was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and retain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to vote, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Citizens today refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education came new demands for participation.
The voters want to be treated as political actors in their own right and not as pawns in the chess game of others.
In addition, governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
That is one of the harsh lessons we had to learn during the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – allow for no solutions from national governments alone.
These challenges demand profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at the subnational and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and entrenched support networks.
Who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well no longer needs a party apparatus that is centuries old.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "backoffice"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
In La République En Marche! we refer to this as local civic projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to community vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering solutions tailored to local problems in order to strengthen the communities in this way.
Such projects should today be seen as indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding avenues for political and community engagement will be crucial to its appeal.
And by daily demonstrating their reform policies "live," the parties have already laid the groundwork for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what you have to say, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the harsh lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Restoring the connection to voters' concerns therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive politics at the local level.
